fonline access with authorization2star  aThe authors of Narrating The Nile seek to encourage the study of Egypt, Sudan, and Ethiopia not only as autonomous entities, but also as part of the Nile region, a shared theater of experiences, national identities, and collective memories. Combining in-depth historical studies and broad interdisciplinary discussions, they provide fresh perspectives on the region's politics and cultures—and on the role the river has played in shaping them from early modern history to contemporary times. The book is published in honor of Professor Haggai Erlich on the occasion of his retirement from Tel Aviv University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh1 aBashkin, Orit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGershoni, Israel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGershoni, Israel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGinat, Rami, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatina, Meir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatina, Meir, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaplan, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharkey, Heather J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShinn, David H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVoll, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWinter, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook packag